   <methods>
      <methodStep>
         <description>
  <para><emphasis>This section contains specific methods for this dataset.</emphasis></para>
  <para> * BIOMASS:LAI CLIPPING SUBSET of CLIP PLOT data </para>
  <para>In order to be able to convert foliar biomass into leaf area, a subset of the harvested clip plot samples was used. For three shrub species (BCCHLM, IVAFRT, and MYRCRF), a herbaceous "nettle" species, two sedges (SCRAMR and SCRRBS), and one salt marsh grass (SPRALT), a subset of the live leaf fraction from the clip plot was set aside. Along with certain standard reference objects (US dollars and coins, a credit card, and a playing card) used to correct for potential photocopier distortion due to scaling changes, the leaves of these subsamples were first photocopied before being dried and weighed. The photocopied pages were then scanned into a computer and the area of the leaves determined using the methodology of O'Neal, Landis, and Isaacs (2002. An inexpensive accurate method for measuring leaf area and defoliation through digital image analysis. Journal of Economic Entomology 95 (6): 1190-1194.) with the following modifications: 1.) the leaves were photocopied and the photocopies scanned into a computer rather than scanning the leaves directly; 2.) contrast-stretching and modifying of the gray-scale curves to create a pure black-and-white image was done in Adobe Photoshop rather than within the Scion Image program used to conduct the measurements; and 3.) a horizontal:vertical pixel aspect ratio of 0.996 in conjunction with an overall correction factor of 1.0232 was applied to the measured leaf areas to correct for very slight reductions in size by the photocopier. Average post-correction accuracy for the standards was within +- 0.5% of the known area, which was also within 1 SE of the mean. This is all within the larger rough estimate of +- 2-3 % error due to incompletely removed shadows and pixelated leaf outlines.</para>
         </description>
      </methodStep>
   </methods>
